China Stocks: Anhui Conch, Huaxin Cement, Qingdao Haier, Vanke

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-04-07T08:18:52Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-07/china-railway-haier-vanke-sinopec-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in China trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 3 p.m. close.  The Shanghai Composite Index climbed 0.2 percent to
3,007.91. The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  rose 0.4 percent to 3,324.42.  Anhui Conch  Cement Co. (600585 CH), the biggest cement
producer, surged 4.9 percent to 42.83 yuan, the highest since
October 2007. Macquarie Group Ltd. boosted Anhui Conch’s stock
rating to “outperform” from “neutral,” citing the company’s
“strong” 2010 earnings and “positive” profit forecast for
the first quarter. JPMorgan Chase & Co. today kept its
“overweight” rating. Anhui Conch said yesterday that profit
for the first three months may have gained more than 150
percent.  Huaxin Cement Co. (600801 CH) surged 10 percent to 54.71
yuan.  China Vanke Co. (000002 CH), the nation’s largest property
developer by market value, climbed 2.4 percent to 9.15 yuan, the
highest since Nov. 11. The company reported a 48 percent jump in
March sales and Goldman Sachs Group Inc. upgraded the industry
to “overweight.”  GF Securities Co. (000776 CH) slid the most in a week,
losing 2.6 percent to 39.40 yuan. The brokerage’s 2010 net
income declined 14 percent from a year earlier to 4 billion yuan
($611 million), according to a statement to Shenzhen’s stock
exchange.  Qingdao Haier Co. (600690 CH) gained the most since Feb.
28, rising 5.1 percent to 29.10 yuan. The company said a
shareholder, Qingdao Haier Venture Investment, may increase its
stake in the Shanghai-listed company by as much as 1.97 percent
in the next 12 months by buying shares, according to a statement
to the stock exchange.  --Irene Shen, Ying Wang. Editor: Allen Wan  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
